excerpt: Huge 11th-century fortress complex on a hilltop with views over city to the Alps, plus museums.
detail_description: Perched on a hilltop with commanding views of the city and the Alps, Fortress Hohensalzburg is an impressive 11th-century complex that draws in over 1.4 million visitors annually. To avoid the crowds, it's best to arrive early and take a glass funicular or embark on a steep 20-minute walk up Festungsgasse in the Old Town to reach this iconic landmark.
name: Fortress Hohensalzburg

excerpt: Iconic, 17th-century palace with ornamental gardens, plus classical concerts in the lavish ballroom.
detail_description: Mirabell Palace, a 17th-century architectural gem located in Salzburg, is renowned for its ornamental gardens and opulent interior. The palace was featured in the iconic film 'The Sound of Music,' with its gardens serving as the backdrop for memorable scenes. Built by Archbishop Wolf Dietrich in 1606 and later redesigned in Baroque style, the palace boasts exquisite interior decorations including stucco and wall paintings.
name: Mirabell Palace

excerpt: Twin spires top this baroque-style 17th-century cathedral, with a museum housing sacred treasures.
detail_description: Salzburg Cathedral, with its twin spires and baroque-style architecture, is a monumental symbol of the city's religious significance and historical wealth. The cathedral houses a museum that displays sacred treasures, adding to its allure. The building has undergone several reconstructions over the centuries, with the current structure showcasing early Baroque ecclesiastical architecture at its finest. Visitors are captivated by the towering facade and turquoise domes of this 17th-century marvel.
name: Salzburg Cathedral

detail_description: Getreidegasse Street, the main shopping artery of Salzburg since Medieval times, is a must-visit for history and culture enthusiasts. It's home to Mozart's birthplace and features intricately decorated shop signs that harken back to a time when people couldn't read, using symbols to represent their trade. The street winds through beautiful baroque architecture and offers international shopping options alongside historic sites.
name: Getreidegasse Street

excerpt: Catholic church & monastery dating to the 7th century, featuring a cemetery, catacombs & a museum.
detail_description: St. Peter's Abbey, situated in Salzburg, Austria, is a renowned Benedictine monastery and Catholic church with a rich history dating back to the 7th century. Established by Saint Rupert, it stands as one of the oldest abbey-church and monastery complexes in the German-speaking world. The Romanesque St. Peter's Church, built in 1143 and later restored with Baroque and Rococo elements, showcases ornate altarpieces by Martin Johann Schmidt.
name: St. Peter's Abbey

excerpt: Birthplace of Wolfgang Mozart in 1756, now a house museum with tours detailing his young life.
detail_description: Mozart's Birthplace, also known as Mozarts Geburtshaus, is a significant historical site in Salzburg. The yellow townhouse was where Wolfgang Mozart, one of the most influential composers in history, was born and lived for 17 years. Today, it operates as a house museum offering tours that provide insights into Mozart's early life. Visitors can explore three floors filled with personal belongings, musical instruments, family portraits, and other important items related to Mozart.
name: Mozart's Birthplace

excerpt: Family-friendly zoo with animals from Africa, Eurasia, Australia & the Americas, plus dining.
detail_description: Salzburg Zoo Hellbrunn is a family-friendly destination featuring over 1,500 animals from various continents. Originally established in the 15th century as an archbishopric zoological park, it now showcases 150 different species. The zoo's unique topography, nestled next to a cliff leading to the large African savannah, adds to its charm.
name: Salzburg Zoo Hellbrunn

excerpt: Rocky plateau above Salzburg with woods, meadows, castles & a modern art museum, reached by a lift.
detail_description: Mönchsberg, also known as Monks Hill, is a rocky plateau above Salzburg offering stunning views of the old town and the Alps. This wooded ridge features meadows, castles, and a modern art museum that can be reached by a lift. The area is home to notable attractions such as the Benedictine Abbey of St. Peter with buildings dating back to the 17th and 18th centuries, including a church remodeled in Rococo style.
name: Mönchsberg

excerpt: Sumptuous 16th-century square centering on a baroque fountain, used for music & sporting events.
detail_description: Residenzplatz is a magnificent 16th-century square featuring a stunning baroque fountain and serving as the backdrop for various cultural events. It holds historical significance, being featured in famous films like The Sound of Music. Visitors can explore nearby attractions such as Mirabell Palace and Garden, Felsenreitschule, St. Peters cemetery, Schloss Leopoldskron, and Nonnberg Convent.
name: Residenzplatz

excerpt: A UNESCO World Heritage Site, this expansive Baroque complex offers art & cultural history tours.
detail_description: The DomQuartier Salzburg is a UNESCO World Heritage Site that showcases the rich arts and cultural history of Salzburg. This expansive Baroque complex includes a cathedral, an Abbey, and five separate museums. One of the museums, the famous Dom Museum, houses the Kunst und Wunderkammer, which features a fascinating collection of stuffed animals, fossils, scientific devices, and rock crystal grinding works.
name: DomQuartier Salzburg

excerpt: Panoramic city views feature from this scenic hill with a circa-1600s Capucines cloister & eatery.
detail_description: Kapuzinerberg is a picturesque hill in Salzburg offering stunning city views and featuring a Capucines cloister dating back to the 1600s. Visitors can enjoy a mix of nature and culture by hiking to Franziskischlossel, indulging in local cuisine, exploring churches and museums, and attending concerts. The area is also described as gay-friendly, with opportunities for biking adventures and positive feedback from the LGBT community.
name: Kapuzinerberg

excerpt: Massive, interactive science & natural history museum, also offering an aquarium & reptile zoo.
detail_description: The Haus der Natur, also known as the Museum of Natural History and Technology, is a captivating science and natural history museum located in Salzburg, Austria. This expansive museum offers a wide range of interactive exhibits suitable for all ages. Visitors can explore permanent displays such as an aquarium and reptile zoo with over 35 tanks showcasing animals from around the world. Additionally, there's an interactive science center providing hands-on experiences to learn about various topics including energy and the human body.
name: Haus der Natur

excerpt: Salzburg is an Austrian city on the border of Germany, with views of the Eastern Alps. The city is divided by the Salzach River, with medieval and baroque buildings of the pedestrian Altstadt (Old City) on its left bank, facing the 19th-century Neustadt (New City) on its right. The Altstadt birthplace of famed composer Mozart is preserved as a museum displaying his childhood instruments.
detail_description: Salzburg, an Austrian city near the German border, offers stunning views of the Eastern Alps. Divided by the Salzach River, it features a medieval Altstadt on one bank and a 19th-century Neustadt on the other. The birthplace of Mozart is now a museum showcasing his childhood instruments. Known for being the setting of The Sound Of Music, Salzburg is a must-see destination with guided tours to its filming locations.
name: Salzburg

excerpt: This large courtyard is best known for its memorial statue of composer Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart.
detail_description: Mozartplatz is a spacious courtyard located in the heart of Salzburg's Old Town, featuring a striking memorial statue of the renowned composer Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart. The square is home to various museums and attractions, such as the Salzburg Museum, Traklhaus, and The Salzburg Christmas Museum. Additionally, adjacent squares like Residenplaz and Domplaz are easily accessible from Mozartplatz.
name: Mozartplatz

detail_description: Salzach River offers a variety of experiences for visitors to Salzburg. One option is to take a cruise along the river, with different tour lengths available, providing stunning views of the city and surrounding alps. Another way to enjoy the river is by taking a leisurely stroll along its banks, offering picturesque vistas and photo opportunities of the city skyline and Hohensalzburg fortress. The northern point near Mirabell Gardens provides an especially beautiful view at sunset or in the early morning.
name: Salzach

detail_description: Grünmarkt is a classic market located in Salzburg's old town, offering a variety of local products from the region. Visitors can find beautiful flowers, fresh fruits and vegetables, as well as organic bread. The market also features its own organic area on Saturdays with various vendors including bakers, butchers, cheese makers and more. Despite being crowded at times, the friendly and helpful sellers make it a pleasant experience for both city dwellers and tourists.
name: Grünmarkt

excerpt: Baroque-style museum with a courtyard, showcasing graphics & photographs by modern Austrian artists.
detail_description: Museum der Moderne Salzburg, located in the New Residential Palace (Neue Residenz), is a must-visit for art and cultural history enthusiasts. The museum showcases modern Austrian artists' graphics and photographs within its Baroque-style architecture. With 3,000 square meters of renovated space, visitors can immerse themselves in multimedia-enhanced exhibitions that range from Bronze Age artifacts to rare 16th-century musical instruments.
name: Museum der Moderne Salzburg

excerpt: Historic 1893 building converted into an auditorium & stage for classic marionette productions.
detail_description: The Salzburger Marionettentheater is housed in a historic 1893 building that has been transformed into an auditorium and stage for classic marionette productions. The theater, a UNESCO World Heritage-listed site, boasts an opulent setting with stucco ornamentation and chandeliers. The attention to detail in costumes and backdrops is remarkable, and the skilled puppeteers bring wooden puppets to life with their expertise.
name: Salzburger Marionettentheater

excerpt: Spacious art museum featuring contemporary & 19th-century works by Salzburg artists.
detail_description: The Salzburg Museum, located in the New Residential Palace (Neue Residenz), is a spacious art museum showcasing contemporary and 19th-century works by local artists. Spanning 3,000 square meters, this museum offers immersive exhibitions that include Bronze Age salt mining artifacts, rare musical instruments from the 16th century, and The Salzburg Myth display exploring the city's Romantic Transfiguration.
name: Salzburg Museum

excerpt: This museum boasts a circular painting of Salzburg in 1829 that guests can see through telescopes.
detail_description: The Panorama Museum, situated near Mozart Square, features a remarkable 360-degree painting of Salzburg from the early 19th century. Created by Johann Michael Sattler, this circular artwork offers a glimpse into the city's appearance during Mozart's era. Visitors can use telescopes to observe intricate details of the historical scenery and architecture depicted in the painting. Additionally, the museum showcases supporting exhibits leading up to the main attraction, providing an engaging experience for guests.
name: Panorama Museum
